eighton33岁，母亲Alice La Strange30岁。他于1242年与Isabella Pichard在英国史洛普爾麗頓结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于1296年在英国英格兰斯塔福爾武托希特享年84岁，埋葬在英国英格兰。"},"hr":{"um 1213–1296":"oko 1213.–1296.","1213–1296":"1213–1296.","1216–Female":"1216–preminula","1243–Male":"1243.–preminuo","1181–Male":"1181–preminuo","1185–Female":"1185–preminula","1242":"1242.","1296":"1296.","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"oko 1211.","1243":"1243.","um 1213":"oko 1213.","Leighton, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","England":"Engleska, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"cs":{"um 1213–1296":"okolo 1213–1296","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1216–Female":"1216–Zesnulá","1243–Male":"1243–Zesnulý","1181–Male":"1181–Zesnulý","1185–Female":"1185–Zesnulá","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"okolo 1211","1243":"1243","um 1213":"okolo 1213","Leighton, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, Anglie"},"da":{"um 1213–1296":"omkring 1213–1296","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1216–Female":"1216–Afdød","1243–Male":"1243–Afdød","1181–Male":"1181–Afdød","1185–Female":"1185–Afdød","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"omkring 1211","1243":"1243","um 1213":"omkring 1213","Leighton, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"um 1213–1296":"circa 1213–1296","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1216–Female":"1216–Overleden","1243–Male":"1243–Overleden","1181–Male":"1181–Overleden","1185–Female":"1185–Overleden","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"circa 1211","1243":"1243","um 1213":"circa 1213","Leighton, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"um 1213–1296":"about 1213–1296","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1216–Female":"1216–Deceased","1243–Male":"1243–Deceased","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1290":"1290","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"about 1211","1243":"1243","um 1213":"about 1213","Leighton, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Layton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Slayton","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Leighton   (compare   Layton  ) with the addition of initial <i>S-</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Sladen   or of <b>Sleightholme</b>, principally a habitational name from Sleightholme Dale in Kirkbymoorside, but perhaps occasionally from Sleightholme in Bowes or the lost Sleightholme in Lythe. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>sléttr</i> ‘smooth, level’ + <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is now very rare in Britain. Compare   Slaydon  ."]},{"name":"Leaton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Letton","meanings":["English: habitational name, most probably from Letton in Norfolk or Latton in Essex. It could also be a variant of   Leighton   or   Laughton  . Most of the places so named have the same etymology as Letton and Latton, i.e. ‘farm where leeks are grown’ (Old English <i>lēac-tūn</i>). Another possibility is that it is a variant of   Latten  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":2,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":11,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":46,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":77,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Leighton was born about 1213, in Leighton, Shropshire, England, his father, Richard de Leighton, was 33 and his mother, Alice La Strange, was 30. He married Isabella Pichard in 1242, in Leighton, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He